2 Quick summaries

myPlot <- function(X) {
  set.seed(1)
  X <- substitute(X)
  ggplot( samples[samples$Run %in% round2,] %>%
            gdata::drop.levels() %>%
            sample_frac) +
    coord_flip() +
    geom_jitter( width = 0.3
               , aes( color=Experiment
                    , Group
                    , eval(X))) +
    ylab(deparse(X))
}

2.1 Indicators that scale with depth.

Values for CAGE_5 should be lower, since it had only one HiSeq lane.

2.1.1 Number of genes detected.

myPlot(genes)

2.1.2 Number of L1 TSS detected.

myPlot(l1)

2.1.3 Number of molecules detected.

myPlot(counts)

2.2 Indicators that should not vary with depth

2.2.1 Richness (scale of 100)

myPlot(r100l1)

2.2.2 cDNA concentration

CAGE_4 run looks cleaner.

myPlot(Concentration)

2.2.3 Spikes

According to empty chambers, the amount of spikes varied between runs. (CAGE_4 > CAGE_5 > CAGE_6).

myPlot(spikes / total)

2.2.4 rRNA

Empty chambers indicate background values (environmental contaminations ?). Negative control shows that spike RNA does not result in significant amounts of artificial rRNA matches.

More rRNA is observed in CAGE_6 when there is a cell, but this can be just a consequence of having less spikes (see above).

myPlot(rdna / total)

2.2.5 rRNA / spikes ratio

Higher in case of the presence of a cell.

myPlot(rdna / spikes)

2.2.6 Tag dust

The CAGE_5 run is much nosier.

myPlot(tagdust / total)
